01:21.920 --> 01:23.420
<i><font size="24"><font face="Arial">it's going to cost you $200{\r}.</font></font></i>

01:23.420 --> 01:24.920
AL:
<i><font size="24"><font face="Arial">$200{\r}?</font></font></i>

01:24.920 --> 01:27.500
We're a three-piece band,
Al, playing six instruments.

01:27.500 --> 01:29.510
All right now,
listen to this.

01:29.510 --> 01:32.260
Before you make an offer, I just
want you to picture something.

01:32.260 --> 01:35.350
It's 6:00, Saturday night.

01:35.350 --> 01:37.260
Milwaukee is
especially boring,

01:37.260 --> 01:39.350
but the word is out.

01:39.350 --> 01:41.550
There's a marathon
dance at Arnold's.

01:41.550 --> 01:44.140
Not just measly records
on the jukebox,

01:44.140 --> 01:46.140
no, we've got a live
band here, Al,

01:46.140 --> 01:48.140
and the place is packed.

01:48.140 --> 01:50.140
The kids... the kids
are very hungry

01:50.140 --> 01:51.640
because the music is so good,

01:51.640 --> 01:53.110
and they want cheeseburgers
at this table.

01:53.110 --> 01:55.150
Over here, they want
to have pizza.

01:55.150 --> 01:56.870
At this table, they
want fish sandwiches.

01:56.870 --> 01:58.950
Oh...

01:58.950 --> 01:59.950
the fish is selling?

01:59.950 --> 02:02.570
Of course it's selling.

02:02.570 --> 02:05.660
Look at this, Al, you have
no room on your grill.

02:05.660 --> 02:07.410
Your freezers are empty.

02:07.410 --> 02:09.130
They're buying the fish?

02:09.130 --> 02:11.210
They're buying
everything, Al.

02:11.710 --> 02:13.720
And by the end of
the marathon dance,

02:13.720 --> 02:15.300
you are completely sold out.

02:15.300 --> 02:17.750
The biggest day in
Arnold's history!

02:17.750 --> 02:20.340
I love it! I love it!

02:20.340 --> 02:22.730
Okay, I'll pay the band $25.

02:22.730 --> 02:25.010
$25?

02:25.010 --> 02:26.100
Oh, forget it,
forget it.

02:26.100 --> 02:27.680
$35 plus a meal.

02:27.680 --> 02:29.270
Will you eat the fish?

02:29.270 --> 02:30.770
No.
You got a deal, Al.

02:30.770 --> 02:32.770
Good bargaining, Ralph,
good bargaining!

02:32.770 --> 02:35.270
Okay, I've got to order
some fish; I'll rent a freezer!

02:35.270 --> 02:38.270
Hey, Chang, they're
buying the fish!

02:38.270 --> 02:40.780
Well, do I drive
a hard bargain

02:40.780 --> 02:42.780
or do I drive
a hard bargain?

02:45.280 --> 02:47.780
He used to be
such a nice guy.

02:47.780 --> 02:48.790
What's wrong?

02:48.790 --> 02:51.040
You're upset because
I closed the deal?

02:51.040 --> 02:53.590
I was trying for $200.

02:56.540 --> 02:58.040
$200?

02:58.550 --> 02:59.550
I heard, I heard.

02:59.550 --> 03:00.550
What do you mean?

03:01.050 --> 03:02.630
How could he ask for $200?

03:02.630 --> 03:05.220
You just signed us up
for a marathon dance, Ralph.

03:05.220 --> 03:07.220
We could be working
for 15 hours.

03:07.220 --> 03:08.810
15 hours?

03:10.270 --> 03:12.230
RALPH:
That's terrible!

03:12.230 --> 03:15.810
That's 15 times
three, into 35...

03:15.810 --> 03:17.730
78 cents an hour.

03:17.730 --> 03:19.320
Look, you can't blame me.

03:19.320 --> 03:21.820
I got us good money,
it's the hours that are bad.

03:21.820 --> 03:23.320
Let's get something
to drink, Pots.

03:23.320 --> 03:24.820
You got money?

03:24.820 --> 03:26.240
No, we'll sip
other people's.
Oh.

03:28.580 --> 03:30.660
(excited chatter)

03:33.160 --> 03:35.160
I'll buy you a malt, Joanie,
you'll forget about them.

03:35.160 --> 03:36.580
Forget?

03:36.580 --> 03:39.800
Forget being cut
from the pom-pom girls?

03:39.800 --> 03:40.890
Oh, you didn't make it, huh?

03:40.890 --> 03:43.920
Do you see pom-poms in my hand?
Well, relax.

03:43.920 --> 03:46.010
Look, it's the first
time you tried out.

03:46.010 --> 03:48.010
Maybe you just
weren't good enough.

03:48.010 --> 03:49.510
Not good enough?
Show him your cheer.

03:49.510 --> 03:51.100
Yeah, watch this.

03:51.100 --> 03:53.180
Hit them high, hit them low,

03:53.180 --> 03:56.100
come on, Jefferson, go, go, go!

03:58.490 --> 03:59.860
Pretty good, huh?

04:02.190 --> 04:04.360
Not bad.

04:04.360 --> 04:05.950
Jill Higgins is the captain.

04:05.950 --> 04:08.080
She's the one who cut me.

04:08.080 --> 04:10.670
Aw, don't you think you're
taking it too seriously?

04:10.670 --> 04:13.670
Big deal. So you didn't make
the pom-poms.

04:13.670 --> 04:15.670
Yeah, Joanie,
it's no big deal.

04:15.670 --> 04:17.170
Well, it is to me.

04:17.170 --> 04:19.130
She's always flaunting
her pom-poms.

04:21.589 --> 04:23.850
Excuse me, Cunningham.

04:23.850 --> 04:26.380
Sure, Higgins.

04:26.380 --> 04:28.690
Jimmy, could I talk to you?

04:28.690 --> 04:30.770
Sure.

04:30.770 --> 04:32.140
Come on,
we'll have a malt.

04:32.140 --> 04:35.280
Jimmy, where are you going?

04:35.280 --> 04:37.360
With Jill.

04:37.360 --> 04:38.230
She's a pom-pom.

04:43.530 --> 04:45.620
I can't take it anymore,
I can't take it.

04:45.620 --> 04:47.120
She beats me at everything.

04:47.620 --> 04:49.120
When we did our science project,

04:49.120 --> 04:50.990
her snake swallowed
my white mouse.

04:55.750 --> 04:59.330
I always wondered
whatever happened to Herbert.

04:59.330 --> 05:01.830
♪ La, la, la, la,
la, la, la ♪

05:01.830 --> 05:03.420
♪ La, la, la. ♪

05:03.420 --> 05:07.010
Joanie, I know you can beat that
pom-pom at the marathon dance.

05:07.510 --> 05:10.010
Well, not only am I not
entering the dance marathon,

05:10.010 --> 05:11.510
I'm not even going.

05:11.510 --> 05:12.480
What do you mean,
you're not going?

05:12.480 --> 05:13.980
We're all going.

05:13.980 --> 05:15.010
I'm going to be a judge,

05:15.520 --> 05:17.020
Mother's going to be
the first aid lady,

05:17.020 --> 05:18.020
and Richie's playing
in the band.

05:18.020 --> 05:19.990
It's almost a
family outing.

05:19.990 --> 05:23.070
I wouldn't have a chance against
her in the dance marathon.

05:23.070 --> 05:25.270
Her partner is
her brother, Bubba.

05:25.270 --> 05:30.110
Well, a Bubba doesn't
sound so hard to beat.

05:30.110 --> 05:35.200
This Bubba lifts
weights, cars, trains...

05:41.790 --> 05:43.380
I gotta tell you,
I gotta tell you,

05:43.380 --> 05:45.380
I'm very sorry that I'm late.

05:45.380 --> 05:47.510
Hey, look at this, huh?

05:47.510 --> 05:50.380
Asparagus... all right.

05:50.380 --> 05:52.640
Corn, huh?

05:52.640 --> 05:55.610
I'll tell you something,
I love being well-balanced.

05:55.610 --> 05:56.690
Heyyy...

06:00.190 --> 06:01.690
Why is everybody staring?

06:01.690 --> 06:03.780
Did I do something wrong?

06:03.780 --> 06:05.110
Is there a hair out of place?

06:07.400 --> 06:08.900
Arthur?
Yeah.

06:08.900 --> 06:12.160
How would you like to enter
a dance marathon?

06:12.160 --> 06:13.740
Well, I'll tell you
something, Mrs. C.,

06:13.740 --> 06:15.240
there's a marathon
I want to enter,

06:15.240 --> 06:17.460
but it's got nothing
to do with dancing.

06:17.460 --> 06:19.160
(laughing)

06:19.160 --> 06:20.250
(laughter continues)

06:23.720 --> 06:28.550
I was talking about
being Joanie's partner.

06:28.550 --> 06:31.140
Oh, hey, no offense, no offense,
but I can't.

06:31.140 --> 06:32.640
See, I promised Eddie Milkis

06:32.640 --> 06:35.180
I'd be his mechanic in a
stock car race in Chicago.

06:35.180 --> 06:36.260
But that's on Friday night.

06:36.260 --> 06:38.820
And you could make it
back in plenty of time.

06:38.820 --> 06:39.900
Oh, listen, Fonzie

06:39.900 --> 06:40.900
doesn't have to help us.

06:40.900 --> 06:41.900
I mean, it's not as if

06:41.900 --> 06:42.900
he's one of the family.

06:44.900 --> 06:46.410
Hey.

06:52.860 --> 06:54.910
Why are you putting
your food back?

06:54.910 --> 06:58.000
Because the Fonz does
nothing out of guilt.

06:58.000 --> 07:00.000
I happen to be a free spirit,

07:00.000 --> 07:02.120
happily motoring
down the road of life.

07:02.120 --> 07:05.170
I want to beat
Jill Higgins.

07:05.170 --> 07:09.260
Jill Higgins, you mean that
little pom pop turnip?

07:09.260 --> 07:10.760
Is she still bugging you?

07:10.760 --> 07:12.220
Yeah, more than ever.

07:12.220 --> 07:14.800
Yeah, and you're Joanie's
only chance of beating her.

07:14.800 --> 07:19.060
I'll tell you, the Fonz's
work is never done.

07:19.060 --> 07:22.360
So, Fonz, are you going
to enter the dance marathon?

07:22.360 --> 07:25.230
Only if this chick
shows me her dimples.

07:26.530 --> 07:28.730
All right.

07:28.730 --> 07:30.320
Okay, let's eat.

07:30.320 --> 07:32.320
Yeah, now I can get
back my veggies.

07:37.870 --> 07:41.380
You are going to be the
handsomest judge at the dance.

07:41.380 --> 07:43.880
And you are going to be
the prettiest first aid lady.

07:43.880 --> 07:45.410
Thank you, dear.

07:45.410 --> 07:47.500
You know,
I haven't dressed like this

07:47.500 --> 07:48.720
since World War II.

07:48.720 --> 07:50.300
Yeah, I know.

07:50.300 --> 07:52.970
I remember when I came home
on furlough, you were so cute.

07:52.970 --> 07:55.560
That's when
we had Joanie.
Yeah.

07:57.060 --> 07:58.430
Oh, boy,

07:58.430 --> 08:01.400
every Saturday
it's the same thing.

08:02.770 --> 08:05.320
When is that kid
going to college?

08:05.320 --> 08:07.400
Joanie will be
down in a minute.

08:07.400 --> 08:08.910
Have you heard
anything from Fonzie?

08:08.910 --> 08:10.910
No, not a word.

08:10.910 --> 08:12.830
Yeah, but you know,
he's always late;

08:12.830 --> 08:14.410
likes to make
the grand entrance

08:14.410 --> 08:15.860
just in the nick of time.

08:15.860 --> 08:17.950
Well, I gotta get going.

08:17.950 --> 08:20.450
Al wants us to get there
a half hour early

08:20.450 --> 08:21.870
to help defrost the fish.

08:23.620 --> 08:25.170
He's so excited.

08:25.170 --> 08:26.710
I'm not very excited.

08:26.710 --> 08:31.210
39 cents an hour and I have to
split it with a girl drummer.

08:31.210 --> 08:32.299
(doorbell chiming)

08:32.299 --> 08:33.299
There's Arthur.

08:33.299 --> 08:34.799
Yeah, what did
I tell you?

08:34.799 --> 08:36.299
Ready for the
grand entrance,

08:36.299 --> 08:38.299
all spruced up and
ready to go, huh?

08:40.470 --> 08:44.520
Uh, like they say,
better late than never.

